Patch summary:
Allow gfxstream's renderer-local udmabuf pool to obtain backing descriptors
from Ika's persistent per-user broker. Some Asahi kernels retain one DMA-BUF
attachment after the renderer closes its DRM file, which pins every udmabuf
folio and makes true userspace reclamation impossible. Keeping the original
descriptors in a broker lets later Cuttlefish processes reuse the same backing
pages instead of allocating another workload-sized set after every VM restart.

The broker is optional. If its socket is unset or unavailable, retain the
existing in-process allocation path.

